<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-831-536  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 831 536.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 10 1990 v24 n37 p23(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A 'welcome' to the battle from a knowing veteran. (ElectronicFrontier Foundation and copyright laws) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ingraham, Donald.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Mitch Kapor of the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF) needs tolearn that the legal structure in the US has been developed inorder to ensure freedoms, and that persons guilty ofcomputer-related crimes should not be exempt from it.andP;  The EFFwould do good to promote a positive discussion on what is meantwhen dealing with civil rights issues in technology.andP;  The lawenforcement community is a bit uncomfortable with some of theEFF's motivation, especially when it maintains the premise thatpersons who are clever enough to commit electronic fraud should beexempt from the criminal process because of their potentialcontribution to computer technology.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic Frontier FoundationCopyrightLegal IssuesComputer Crimes.andO;Person:    Kapor, Mitch (political activity).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>